{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526183"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14124"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14124"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.08,0.16,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1816"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine antenatal visit at 32 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 145/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has no peripheral oedema. Urinalysis shows trace protein. Her blood pressure two weeks ago was 120/80 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urine protein collection","Fetal fibronectin test","Expectant management","Liver function tests","Urine protein-to-creatinine ratio"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with new-onset hypertension after 20 weeks of gestation, which is consistent with gestational hypertension. The next step is to determine if she has progressed to pre-eclampsia, which requires assessment for significant proteinuria or evidence of end-organ dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step is to obtain a \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine protein-to-creatinine ratio\u003C/strong\u003E. This test is the preferred method for quantifying proteinuria in pregnancy as it is quick, convenient, and correlates well with 24-hour urine protein levels. A ratio of \u226530 mg/mmol is considered significant proteinuria in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine protein collection\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally the gold standard for quantifying proteinuria. However, it is time-consuming, inconvenient, and often inaccurate due to incomplete collection. The urine protein-to-creatinine ratio has largely replaced this test in clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efetal fibronectin test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess the risk of preterm labour in women with symptoms of preterm labour. It is not indicated in this scenario where the primary concern is gestational hypertension and potential pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the workup for pre-eclampsia, particularly if there are concerns about HELLP syndrome (Haemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes, Low Platelets). However, they are not the most appropriate next step in this scenario, where quantifying proteinuria is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. The new onset of hypertension requires further investigation and close monitoring. Gestational hypertension can progress to pre-eclampsia, which carries significant risks for both mother and fetus if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter quantifying proteinuria, further management may include more frequent antenatal visits, blood tests (including full blood count, liver function tests, and renal function), and fetal assessment. If pre-eclampsia is diagnosed, the patient may require admission for blood pressure control and monitoring, with timing of delivery based on gestational age and severity of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gestational hypertension is defined as new-onset hypertension after 20 weeks of gestation without proteinuria.","Urine protein-to-creatinine ratio is the preferred method for quantifying proteinuria in pregnancy.","Pre-eclampsia is diagnosed when gestational hypertension is accompanied by significant proteinuria or evidence of end-organ dysfunction."],"references":["Chappell LC, Cluver CA, Kingdom J, et al. Pre-eclampsia. Lancet 2021; 398: 341\u201354."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14124"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-11T10:24:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-11T10:25:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id